    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. I've noticed some legal scholars and conservative judges argue that 'substantive due process' is actually a bit problematic or even unconstitutional because it gives judges too much power to make up rights that aren't explicitly in the text. How would you address that critique in my class? I want them to see the full picture of the debate.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The critique that substantive due process allows judges to \"make up rights\" is a common, yet deeply rooted, conservative argument against judicial activism. Those who hold this view fear that unelected judges are imposing their personal policy preferences onto the Constitution, usurping the role of the elected legislature. However, proponents argue that the Constitution is not merely a list of procedures but a living document designed to protect inherent human rights against the fleeting whims of the majority. This debate highlights the fundamental tension between democratic rule by the people and the necessity of a higher, enduring legal standard for liberty.",
      "source": "target",
